<center><h2>Michael Fumento</h2></center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<blockquote>
<dd>A graduate of the University of Illinois College of Law, Michael 
Fumento is a former AIDS analyst and attorney for the U.S. Commission 
on Civil Rights.  He has been an editorial writer for the Rocky 
Mountain News in Denver and was the first "National Issues" reporter 
for Investor's Business Daily.  Mr. Fumento was the 1994 Warren T. 
Brookes Fellow in Environmental Journalism at the Competitive 
Enterprise Institute in Washington, D.C.   He currently is a fellow 
with Consumer Alert in Washington, D.C., though he works out of his 
home in St. Petersburg, Florida.  His weekly self-syndicated column 
appears in the Washington Times, Detroit News, and other newspapers.   
His articles have also appeared in newspapers and magazines around the 
world, including The American Spectator, The New Republic, Reader's 
Digest, the Washington Monthly, the Sunday Times of London, the New 
York Times, Wall Street Journal, Washington Post, and Los Angeles 
Times.  Mr. Fumento has lectured on science and health issues 
throughout the country and in Europe and Asia.  He has authored two 
books, The Myth of Heterosexual AIDS (1990, revised 1993) and Science 
Under Siege:  Balancing Technology and the Environment (1993).  
Science Under Siege has received two awards, including the American 
Council on Science and Health's "Distinguished Science Journalist of 
1993" award.  
</blockquote>
